### 2. Scientific Foundation (for reference & in-app education)

**Relational Frame Theory (RFT)**: Human intelligence heavily depends on learned ability to derive relations between stimuli (same, different/opposite, more/less, before/after, contains, etc.) even when stimuli are arbitrary (nonsense words, abstract shapes). Training these skills via **Multiple Exemplar Training (MET)** leads to generalized improvements in cognition and academics.

**SMART Mechanics** (publicly described):
- **Stimuli**: Nonsense words (e.g., GYQ, FYW, VOP, CUB, KES) or arbitrary visuals.
- **Premises**: 1–4+ relational statements (e.g., “GYQ is the same as FYW. FYW is more than VOP.”).
- **Probe**: Yes/No question on a derived relation (e.g., “Is GYQ more than VOP?”).
- **Structure**: Training blocks (with feedback) → Test blocks (no feedback). Mastery required to advance.
- **Progression**: ~55 stages increasing in:
  - Number/complexity of premises
  - Types of relations (coordination → opposition → comparison → temporal → hierarchical → combined)
  - Depth of derivation
  - Time pressure / fluency demands
- **Assessment**: Pre/post **Relational Abilities Index (RAI)**-style test (accuracy + speed/fluency).

**Recommended Reading** (include short summaries or links in-app “Science” section):
- Cassidy et al. (2011, 2016), Colbert et al. (2018), McLoughlin et al. (2020+), May et al. meta-analysis, etc.

